{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486645"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:39:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:39:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"150"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/150"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.08,0.01,0.75,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"150"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60117"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/150"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"150"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45537"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18968"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42001"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60117"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman is being reviewed after a pulse rate of 150/min was found on a routine nursing observation on the medical ward. She was admitted three days earlier with community-acquired pneumonia and has been stable on intravenous antibiotic therapy. She has a medical history of osteoarthritis, atrial fibrillation, and previous transient ischaemic attacks. Her regular medications include digoxin 125 microg daily, apixaban, and paracetamol. She is currently asymptomatic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears comfortable. Her pulse rate is 150/min, blood pressure 110/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, and SpO2 95% on oxygen 2 L/min via nasal prongs. An ECG shows atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular response. Her serum digoxin concentration is 1.1 nmol/L (0.6-2.6).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous magnesium sulfate","Intravenous atropine","Oral vitamin K","Intravenous metoprolol","Intravenous digoxin"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular response (150/min) but is haemodynamically stable. Given her therapeutic digoxin level and stable condition, acute rate control with a beta blocker is most appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous metoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice as beta blockers are first-line agents for acute rate control in atrial fibrillation. They act rapidly to slow AV nodal conduction and are particularly effective in the setting of increased sympathetic tone, such as during acute illness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous digoxin\u003C/strong\u003E would provide little additional benefit as the patient is already on maintenance digoxin therapy with a therapeutic level. Furthermore, digoxin has a slow onset of action and is less effective for rate control during acute illness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous magnesium sulfate\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful in treating torsades de pointes or digoxin toxicity, neither of which are present here. The patient\u0027s digoxin level is within the therapeutic range.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous atropine\u003C/strong\u003E is used for treating bradycardia, not tachycardia, and would likely worsen this patient\u0027s rapid ventricular response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral vitamin K\u003C/strong\u003E is used to reverse warfarin anticoagulation. This patient is on apixaban, and there is no indication for anticoagulation reversal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe AFFIRM trial demonstrated that rate control is an appropriate strategy for stable patients with atrial fibrillation, with outcomes at least as good as rhythm control. Beta blockers, calcium channel blockers (diltiazem, verapamil), and digoxin are the main agents used for rate control.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Beta blockers are first-line agents for acute rate control in atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular response.","Rate control is an appropriate strategy for stable patients with atrial fibrillation.","Additional digoxin loading provides little benefit when patients are already taking maintenance digoxin therapy."],"references":["Romero I, Nedios S, Kriatselis C. Diagnosis and Management of Atrial Fibrillation: An Overview. Cardiovascular. Ther 2014; 32:242-52."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45537"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"150"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16"},{"type":"media","id":"17"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f1407ecd-af05-4046-aa11-2e620ae034a9.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f1407ecd-af05-4046-aa11-2e620ae034a9.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,